Introduction¶

This is an analysis made for the project Investigate a Dataset. The dataset I chose for this analysis is TMDb data, which contains information about 10,000 movies collected fromThe Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

We first import the required libraries for the analysis. Pandas is a Python data analysis and manipulation tool which will help us read the csv file and then proceed to analysis. Numpy is a Python library with a large collection of high-level mathematical functions which we gonna need during our research. We gonna need matplotlib in order to have good visualisations of our data. It is also improtant to import the magic function %inline just to be sure that our visualisations will show inline.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

%matplotlib inline

Data Wrangling¶

In this section we will load in the data, check for cleanliness, and then trim and clean the dataset for analysis. Data Wrangling is a very important part in every data analysis project.

The problems that we abserve in this dataset are:¶

  • Certain columns, like cast and genres, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.
  • The final two columns ending with _adj show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, we will also delete those columns as we have 2020 now and 2010 dollars won't be a good practice to examine movies budget.
  • The dataset contain lots of movies where the budget or revenue have a value of '0'.
  • There are some duplicate rows that we will need to delete.

Steps we will follow:¶

  • We gonna keed only the relevant data and deleting the unused columns, such as homepage, id, imdb_id, 'homepage', 'keywords', 'tagline'
  • We will remove the movies which are having zero value of budget and revenue.
  • We will remove dublicated lines
  • We will rename the remaining columns in order to be more specific and easy to understand.
  • We will convert release_date column to datetime.

Data Cleaning (This is the part where the data set is prepared for the analysis and the data wrangling observations are being evaluated in the dataset)¶

Unfortunately, data is not always perfect (actually it is very rare to find perfect data). In this part of the project, we gonna apply the changes to the dataset and then we will begin the analysis. This part is very important on every data analysis because it improves data quality and increases overall productivity and results.

  • We gonna keep only the relevant data and deleting the unused columns, such as homepage, id, imdb_id, 'homepage', 'tagline'.
  • We will convert release_date column to datetime.
  • Reordering the columns so that the dataset can be better inspected.
  • We will remove the movies which are having zero value of budget and revenue.
  • We will remove dublicated lines
  • We will rename the remaining columns in order to be more specific and easier to understand.
  1. The fist step we gonna follow is to delete the unused columns and reinspect tha dataset to be sure that they are deleted. We see the exact column names in order to avoid syntax errors.

profit_year = df.groupby('release_year')['budget'].sum()
sorted_budget = df['budget'].sort_values(ascending=False)[:20]
high_budget=pd.DataFrame()
titles_exp=[]
budgets=[]
for i in sorted_budget.index:
    titles_exp.append(df.loc[i,'title'])
    budgets.append(sorted_budget.loc[i])

# Create title and profit lists which will be used as X-axis and Y-axis values in bar graph.
high_profit=pd.DataFrame()
titles=[]
profit=[]

# Fill the vallues from raw data to the lists.
for i in sorted_profit.index:
    titles.append(df.loc[i,'title'])
    profit.append(sorted_profit.loc[i])
high_profit['Titles']=titles
high_profit['Profit']=profit
high_profit.set_index('Titles',inplace=True)

# Plot

plt.title('Top 10 movies with the most profit');
plt.ylabel('movie profit');
sns.set_style('darkgrid')

Question 3: How many movies per year? Which year had the most movies?¶

In order to make this research we need to visualize the release year in the x axis and the number of movies in the y axis. We will use groupby function stored in the variable movies and we will then print the 10 last rows that are the years with the most movies. From our plot is preety clear that movies number has increased rapidly after 00s.

In [36]:
movies=df.groupby('release_year').count()['title']

df.groupby('release_year').count()['title'].plot(xticks = np.arange(1960,2016,5));
#set the figure size and labels
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(10,5)})
plt.title("Year Vs Number Of Movies",fontsize = 14)
plt.xlabel('Release year',fontsize = 13)
plt.ylabel('Number Of Movies',fontsize = 13)
#set the style sheet
sns.set_style("whitegrid")

As we can se from our results the year with the most movies is 2014 and all the 10 years are after 2000 which shows that our visualization is correct.

If we want to visualize our findings about correlation in order to see the most strong relationship between the variables, we can visualise them with a correlation matrix which is a table showing correlation coefficients between variables.

In [51]:
#We define the function plot_correlation_map in order to vizualise the correlation of the variables
#and find the strongest one.
def plot_correlation_map( df ):
    corr = df.corr()
    _ , ax = plt.subplots( figsize =( 12 , 10 ) )
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette( 240 , 10 , as_cmap = True )
    _ = sns.heatmap(corr,cmap = cmap,square=True, cbar_kws={ 'shrink' : .9 }, ax=ax, annot = True, annot_kws = { 'fontsize' : 12 })
In [52]:
plot_correlation_map(df[['popularity','budget','profit','duration','votes','vote_average']])
  • Budget vs profit : They have a strong relationship of 0.73
  • Popularity vs profit : They have a positive relationship of 0.66. This shows that there is a good possibility that most popular films tend to have better profits.
  • Duration vs profits: The relationship is really weak 0.16. It seems that movie duration is not affecting the movie profits. This could be the reason that movies length is decreasing through the years.

We will now plot the increase of the movie's profit as years go by.

profits_each_year = df.groupby('release_year')['profit'].sum()

It's obvious that movie profits increase is incredible and especially after 00s we see an enormous increase. We can observe that during 60s and 70s movies profit was extremely low. That explains the fact that all the high budget movies where during the 00s. And high profit as well. The main cause could be the fact that humanity tends to get richer so the movies do.

Question 6: Which genres are most popular from year to year?¶

In order to find out the most popular genres throught the years, we will construct a new dataframe that separates the genres and then calculate the number of movies in each genre. Then we will visualise our results in order to see the most popular genre throught the years. The best way to visualize our findings will be a bar chart and a pie chart. We will use matplotlib in order to extract the charts that we want.

In [54]:
#In order to find the most popular genres per year we construct df_split_genre
df_split_genre = df.copy()
#In order to find the most popular genres per year we define the function df_split_genre
#remove the ('|') from the genres column
split_genre = df_split_genre['genres'].str.split('|').apply(pd.Series, 1
).stack().reset_index(level=1, drop=True)

split_genre.name = 'genre_split'
df_split_genre = df_split_genre.drop(['genres'], axis=1).join(split_genre)
In [55]:
#plot the result in a barchart
df_split_genre['genre_split'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', figsize=(15, 8));
#Adding plot title

plt.xlabel('Genre', size=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of movies', size=12);

df_split_genre['genre_split'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', figsize=(9,9), autopct="%1.1f%%");

We can visualise our result with a pie chart as well that calculates the percentage of the genres popularity. We can see that drama is the most popular genre all those years. Comedy is 2nd and thriller 3rd. Those are the movie genres that people prefer. We can also visualize our results in a pie chart and see the percentages as well.

Limitations¶

Although we cleaned our data, there were still some things that we needed to consider:

  • We have used TMBD Movies dataset for our analysis and worked with popularity, revenue and runtime. Our analysis is limited to only the provided dataset. For example, the dataset does not confirm that every release of every director is listed.
  • Maybe we could expand our analysis with more data movies from other databases. IMDB would be a good case.
  • We were not normalized or exchanged the currency conversion during this analysis, we were just limited to the numerical values of revenue.
  • Dropping missing or Null values from variables of our interest might skew our analysis and could show unintentional bias towards the relationship being analyzed. etc.
  • We were not able to find a really strong relationship in terms of correlation between the popularity and the popularity and vote average. This could be further investigated because the logic says that popular films should have more votes. This could be due to the 0s that we chose not to drop (this could skew our analysis and we would possibly not be able to collect good results.)
  • We were not be able to find a relationship between duration and profits. This could be the reason that directors choose to direct short films. Or maybe short films are easier to watch? Longer films could make the audience tired sooner. This could be further analysed in the future.
